    <h1>I have always prided myself on my diverse taste in music.</h1>
    <p>Although heavy metal was my first love, I’ve come a long way since I was a 12-year-old headbanging to Metallica. Music has many genres and styles, and I’ve learned to appreciate something about pretty much all of them. Some music will evoke different moods - jazz is nice for quiet, rainy mornings sipping tea, but less ideal for workouts or runs. Metal is obviously the exact opposite. Hip hop makes me feel like I’m back in the ‘90s, riding around in my nonexistent Cadillac convertible and smoking cigars. Classic rock makes me want to yell at small children to get off my lawn. You get the idea. </p>

    <p>But there is one godforsaken genre that has almost zero redeeming qualities. It is repetitive, uncreative, and bland. The instruments are dull, taking a back seat to the vocals, which are usually even worse. The lyrics…god. I would rather bathe in razor blades than listen to hillbillies moan about their broken tractor or yodel about how much they want to bang their cousin. </p>
    <p>I’m talking about Country, of course. The genre of my home state, country may at one point have conjured images of gunslingers, outlaws, and fast horses, but today seems to be marketed more towards sorority girls who drive Jeep Wranglers exclusively to and from Starbucks. “Country” folk love to sing about farmwork and manual labor, yet all of them sound like they’re recording from their mansion in Malibu. Every time my friends tell me to “just give it a chance” or throw on some country in their car, I really, really do try to listen.</p>
