    <p>But all of the songs are so same-y, contain no interesting, you know, MUSIC, and sport some of the shittiest singing you can listen to on the radio. I mean metal has awful singing too, probably the worst on average, but at least makes up for it with sick instrumentation and cool guitar solos. Country has...cowboy chords?</p>
    <p>BUT. There is a silver lining here. Sort of.</p>
    <p>It’s called BLUEGRASS, and it’s basically Country’s cousin, except he’s older, more mature, doesn’t smell, and owns like 4 yachts because he’s awesome. Bluegrass is typically much faster and more upbeat, with a variety of instruments being featured, from flatpicked acoustic guitars to banjos to fiddles to harmonicas. Typically, one instrument will play melody and improvise over it; everybody else plays rhythm, and the cycle repeats with the instruments switching out. In this way, Bluegrass is a bit like jazz or blues music, mashed together with country.</p>
    <p>As a result, the instruments are actually fun to listen to. Some of the guitar solos can sound almost like metal, with how fast and technical the phrasing is. The singing is also generally a vast improvement; while I’m not a fan of some hillbilly-sounding singers, I think overall most bluegrass singers are much more pleasant to listen to than country.</p>
    <p>I've spent the past couple of weeks listening to more and more bluegrass and I've gotta say, I've been pleasantly surprised. There's plenty of good music out there, and I think bluegrass manages to capture that old-timey western feel that Country goes for, while still having fast-paced and cool instruments to listen to. The fact that the singing ranges from tolerable to actually really good is just the icing on the cake. Check out some of the songs I've been listening to recently:</p>
